In the degrees as well of Masters of Arts, as of Doctors of Divinity, let three things be observed: First, let no one be advanced until he be diligently and publicly examined by persons appointed, who shall carefully perform this duty, and he shall be found qualified for that Science, whether he belong to the Society, or not3 Secondly, That the door may be closed against Ambition, no fixed places shall be assigned to those who are raised to Degrees; but let them rather study in honour to prefer one another, without observing any difference of places: Thirdly, As the Society instructs gratuitously‚ so let it raise to degrees gratuitously; and to those without the Society, let very little expense, although voluntary, be permitted, lest custom at length obtain the force of law3 and in this point in the course of time they exceed moderation. CHAP. XVI.

And each of the Preceptors will take care that this be done by his pupils.
